Strophic form also called verserepeating chorus form the term applied songs which all verses stanzas the text are sung the same music The opposite strophic form with new music written for every stanza called throughcomposed The term derived from the Greek word stroph meaning turn the simplest and most durable musical forms extending piece music repetition single formal section This may analyzed This additive method the musical analogue repeated stanzas poetry lyrics and fact where the text repeats the same rhyme scheme from one stanza the next the songs structure also often uses either the same very similar material from one stanza the next modified strophic form varies the pattern some stanzas somewhat like rudimentary theme and variations Contrasting versechorus form binary form that alternates between two sections music ABAB although this may also interpreted constituting larger strophic verserefrain form While the terms refrain and chorus are often used interchangeably refrain may indicate recurring line identical melody and lyrics part the verse Blowing The Wind the answer friend while chorus means independent form section Yellow Submarine all live Many folk and popular songs are strophic form including the twelve bar blues ballads hymns and chants Examples include Barbara Allen Erie Canal and Michael Row the Boat Ashore Also Susanna verse chorus Many classical art songs are also composed strophic form from the 17th century French air cour 19th century German lieder and beyond Haydn used the strophic variation form many his string quartets and few his symphonies employed almost always the slow second movement Franz Schubert composed many important strophic lieder including settings both narrative poems and simpler folklike texts such his Heidenrslein and Der Fischer Several the songs his song cycle Die schne Mllerin use strophic form Appen Ralf von FreiHauenschild Markus AABA Refrain Chorus Bridge Prechorus Song Forms and their Historical Development Samples On